WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.160 --> 00:00:04.586
Professor Shelly Kagan:
We've been talking about the

00:00:04.586 --> 00:00:08.013
question as to whether or not it
would be desirable to live

00:00:08.013 --> 00:00:11.498
forever, whether immortality
would actually be a good thing,

00:00:11.498 --> 00:00:14.275
as most of normally presume,
or whether in fact,

00:00:14.275 --> 00:00:17.820
as Bernard Williams argues,
it would be undesirable.

00:00:17.820 --> 00:00:21.467
The question we turned to was,
just let your imagination run

00:00:21.467 --> 00:00:23.779
free.
Instead of asking what would it

00:00:23.779 --> 00:00:27.296
be like to continue living a
longer kind of trajectory that

00:00:27.296 --> 00:00:30.812
humans have in the real world
where you just get sicker and

00:00:30.812 --> 00:00:33.420
more and more frail and
incapacitated,

00:00:33.420 --> 00:00:36.016
ask yourself not whether
immortality of that sort

00:00:36.016 --> 00:00:38.266
would be valuable,
but is it even so much as

00:00:38.266 --> 00:00:41.455
possible to describe a
life that you would want to live

00:00:41.455 --> 00:00:44.390
forever?
That's the question I left you

00:00:44.390 --> 00:00:47.931
with last time.
I think I already tipped my

00:00:47.931 --> 00:00:51.350
cards on this matter.
I'm inclined to agree with

00:00:51.350 --> 00:00:54.442
Williams.
I think that no matter how we

00:00:54.442 --> 00:00:58.740
try to fill in the blank,
it's a very long blank.

00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:01.985
The crucial point here for us
is that immortality means not

00:01:01.985 --> 00:01:05.286
just living a very long time or
even an extraordinarily long

00:01:05.286 --> 00:01:07.810
time,
but literally living forever.

00:01:07.810 --> 00:01:11.361
I think it's very difficult,
indeed I think it's impossible,

00:01:11.361 --> 00:01:14.250
to think of anything you'd want
to do forever.

00:01:14.250 --> 00:01:17.253
I have a friend who once
claimed to me that he wanted to

00:01:17.253 --> 00:01:20.584
live forever so that he could
have Thai food every day for the

00:01:20.584 --> 00:01:23.650
rest of,
well, the rest of eternity.

00:01:23.650 --> 00:01:27.453
I like Thai food just fine,
but the prospect of having Thai

00:01:27.453 --> 00:01:31.060
food day after day after day
after day for thousands,

00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:34.554
millions, billions,
trillions of years no longer

00:01:34.554 --> 00:01:38.431
seems an attractive proposal.
It seems like it becomes some

00:01:38.431 --> 00:01:40.892
kind of a nightmare.
And the same way that I

00:01:40.892 --> 00:01:43.938
indicated previously that
although I like chocolate--I

00:01:43.938 --> 00:01:47.158
love chocolate--the
prospect of having to eat more

00:01:47.158 --> 00:01:50.090
and more and more and more and
more chocolate,

00:01:50.090 --> 00:01:53.300
eventually the idea becomes a
sickening one.

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:56.036
Think of any activity.
Some of you may enjoy doing

00:01:56.036 --> 00:01:58.813
crossword puzzles,
and perhaps doing crossword

00:01:58.813 --> 00:02:01.590
puzzles a couple hours a day is
enjoyable.

00:02:01.590 --> 00:02:05.795
But imagine doing crossword
puzzles every day for 10 years,

00:02:05.795 --> 00:02:07.825
1,000 years,
a million years,

00:02:07.825 --> 00:02:10.580
a billion years,
a trillion years.

00:02:10.580 --> 00:02:13.840
Eventually, presumably,
so it seems to me,

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:17.816
you'd end up saying,
"I'm really tired of crossword

00:02:17.816 --> 00:02:21.054
puzzles."
Sure, there'd be some new

00:02:21.054 --> 00:02:26.169
particular puzzle you hadn't
seen before, but you'd sort of

00:02:26.169 --> 00:02:30.313
step up a level and say,
"Although I haven't seen this

00:02:30.313 --> 00:02:33.292
particular one before,
I've seen crossword puzzles

00:02:33.292 --> 00:02:35.833
before.
There's really nothing new

00:02:35.833 --> 00:02:38.967
under the sun here.
The fact that I haven't seen

00:02:38.967 --> 00:02:42.438
this particular combination of
words isn't enough to make it

00:02:42.438 --> 00:02:45.190
interesting."
Well, crossword puzzles aren't

00:02:45.190 --> 00:02:48.207
a very deep subject,
and we might wonder whether or

00:02:48.207 --> 00:02:51.707
not we would do better if we
were engaged in something more

00:02:51.707 --> 00:02:55.910
mentally challenging than that.
This may indicate something

00:02:55.910 --> 00:02:59.069
unusual about me,
but I rather like math.

00:02:59.069 --> 00:03:02.729
And the prospect of having a
lot of time to pursue math

00:03:02.729 --> 00:03:07.000
problems of a richer and deeper
sort seems fairly attractive.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.757
Yet even there,
when I imagine an eternity of

00:03:09.757 --> 00:03:12.389
thinking about math--or for that
matter,

00:03:12.389 --> 00:03:16.468
an eternity of thinking about
philosophy, which I obviously

00:03:16.468 --> 00:03:20.617
like even more than math--the
prospect seems an unattractive

00:03:20.617 --> 00:03:23.253
one.
I can't think of any activity

00:03:23.253 --> 00:03:26.462
I'd want to do forever.
Now, of course,

00:03:26.462 --> 00:03:30.099
that's a bit of a cheat because
the claim isn't to spend

00:03:30.099 --> 00:03:34.199
eternity doing math problems and
nothing but math problems.

00:03:34.199 --> 00:03:38.150
Right now, with our 50,80,
100 years, we don't fill our

00:03:38.150 --> 00:03:40.930
day doing only one kind of
activity.

00:03:40.930 --> 00:03:45.650
We fill our day with a mixture
of activities.

00:03:45.650 --> 00:03:49.973
But it doesn't really help
having Thai food for dinner and

00:03:49.973 --> 00:03:53.023
Chinese for lunch.
Or perhaps Chinese on Monday,

00:03:53.023 --> 00:03:55.985
Wednesdays, and Fridays and
Thai on Saturdays and Sundays

00:03:55.985 --> 00:03:59.105
and spending two hours in the
afternoon doing math and three

00:03:59.105 --> 00:04:01.379
hours in the morning doing
philosophy.

00:04:01.379 --> 00:04:03.699
That sounds like a pretty
pleasant life.

00:04:03.699 --> 00:04:07.930
But again, if you think of the
possibility of doing that for

00:04:07.930 --> 00:04:11.729
all eternity and never
getting away from it,

00:04:11.729 --> 00:04:15.859
never being free from it,
the positive dream of

00:04:15.859 --> 00:04:19.810
immortality, I think,
becomes a nightmare.

00:04:19.810 --> 00:04:23.591
Well again, maybe I'm not just
being creative enough in my

00:04:23.591 --> 00:04:26.935
imagination.
Different former colleague of

00:04:26.935 --> 00:04:31.431
mine once talked about the
prospect of having a kind of

00:04:31.431 --> 00:04:36.065
heavenly vision of the divine.
Maybe that would be desirable

00:04:36.065 --> 00:04:38.019
forever.
And she described it as,

00:04:38.019 --> 00:04:41.613
think of what it's like to have
a really great conversation with

00:04:41.613 --> 00:04:44.009
a friend that you wish would
never end,

00:04:44.009 --> 00:04:47.530
except God's this infinitely
rich friend and so the

00:04:47.530 --> 00:04:50.980
conversation ends up seeming
desirable forever.

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:55.225
Well again, I can say the
words, but when I try to imagine

00:04:55.225 --> 00:04:58.279
that possibility and take it
seriously,

00:04:58.279 --> 00:05:02.350
at least speaking personally,
it doesn't--it doesn't hold up.

00:05:02.350 --> 00:05:07.261
No friend that I've ever talked
with is one that I actually

00:05:07.261 --> 00:05:11.410
would want to spend
eternity talking to.

00:05:11.410 --> 00:05:14.632
And it's of course possible to
say, well, just imagine a friend

00:05:14.632 --> 00:05:17.439
that you would want to talk
through all eternity to.

00:05:17.439 --> 00:05:20.604
But the whole point is,
I can't imagine what that would

00:05:20.604 --> 00:05:23.257
be like.
When I do my best to imagine

00:05:23.257 --> 00:05:27.613
some kind of existence that
would be desirable or attractive

00:05:27.613 --> 00:05:32.279
forever, it just doesn't work.
It becomes a nightmare.

00:05:32.279 --> 00:05:35.332
Well again, maybe what we need
to do is not so much just

00:05:35.332 --> 00:05:38.606
imagine the same cycling going
through week after week after

00:05:38.606 --> 00:05:42.682
week, but whole careers.
Maybe you could spend 50 or 100

00:05:42.682 --> 00:05:46.100
years pursuing philosophy as
your career.

00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:49.519
And then 50 or 100 years
pursuing math as your career.

00:05:49.519 --> 00:05:52.329
And 50 or 100 years traveling
around the world.

00:05:52.329 --> 00:05:57.511
And 50 or 100 years being an
artist and working on your water

00:05:57.511 --> 00:06:01.500
colors, or whatever it is.
Well, that certainly seems like

00:06:01.500 --> 00:06:03.779
we could probably get more time
out of that.

00:06:03.779 --> 00:06:07.445
But again, the crucial point to
remember is that forever is

00:06:07.445 --> 00:06:11.262
literally forever.
There's no life that I'm

00:06:11.262 --> 00:06:15.955
able to imagine for myself
that's one that I would want to

00:06:15.955 --> 00:06:17.520
take on forever.

00:06:20.939 --> 00:06:24.713
Well, you might say surely
there could be creatures that

00:06:24.713 --> 00:06:28.350
would want to live
forever, that would enjoy an

00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:31.718
eternal existence.
And I think that's probably

00:06:31.718 --> 00:06:33.635
right.
